es with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1             = \n|leader_title2            = \n|leader_name2             = \n|leader_title3            = \n|leader_name3             = \n|leader_title4            = \n|leader_name4             = \n|established_title        = Settled\n|established_date         = 1859\n|established_title2       = <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|established_date2        = \n|established_title3       = <!-- Incorporated (city) -->\n|established_date3        = \n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude           = \n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_total_km2           = 30.1\n|area_land_km2            = 30.0\n|area_water_km2           = 0.2\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 11.6\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 11.6\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.1\n|area_water_percent       = 0.52\n|area_urban_km2           = \n|area_urban_sq_mi         = \n|area_metro_km2           = \n|area_metro_sq_mi         = \n|area_blank1_title        = \n|area_blank1_km2          = \n|area_blank1_sq_mi        = \n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_note          = \n|population_total         = 9038\n|population_density_km2   = 307.2\n|population_density_sq_mi = 795.7\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_metro_km2     = \n|population_density_metro_sq_mi   = \n|population_urban                 = \n|population_density_urban_km2     = \n|population_density_urban_sq_mi   = \n|population_blank1_title          = \n|population_blank1                = \n|population_density_blank1_km2    = \n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi  = \n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone                 = [[Mountain Time Zone|MST]]\n|utc_offset               = -7\n|timezone_DST             = [[Mountain Time Zone|MDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = -6\n|coordinates              = {{coord|39|38|20|N|105|20|11|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes      = <!--for references: use 1 tags-->\n|elevation_m              = 2200.6\n|elevation_ft             = 7220\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]s<ref name=ZIPcode>{{cite web|date=December 14, 2006 |url=http://zip4.usps.com/zip4/citytown.jsp |title=ZIP Code Lookup |format=[[JavaScript]]/[[HTML]] |publisher=United States Postal Service |accessdate=December 14, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104123722/http://zip4.usps.com/zip4/citytown.jsp |archivedate=November 4, 2010 }}</ref>\n|postal_code              = 80439, 80437\n|area_code                = [[Area code 303|303]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 08-25390\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0204712\n|website                  = [http://www.evergreenchamber.org Evergreen Area Chamber of Commerce]  \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n<!-- Infobox ends -->\n\n'''Evergreen''' is a [[census-designated place]] (CDP) and a [[United States Postal Service|U.S. Post Office]] in [[Jefferson County, Colorado|Jefferson County]], [[Colorado]], United States.  Evergreen is roughly {{convert|29|mi|km}} west of [[Denver]]. The population was 9,038 at the [[United States Census, 2010|2010 census]].<ref>[http://mcdc.missouri.edu/webrepts/pl94trends/Colorado_stplace2.html Colorado Trend Report 2: State and Complete Places (Sub-state 2010 Census Data).] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120711184447/http://mcdc.missouri.edu/webrepts/pl94trends/Colorado_stplace2.html |date=2012-07-11 }} Missouri Census Data Center. Accessed 2011-02-25.</ref><ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nA post office called Evergreen has been in operation since 1876.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postalhistory.com/postoffices.asp?state=CO |title=Post offices |publisher=Jim Forte Postal History |accessdate=25 June 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306120236/http://www.postalhistory.com/postoffices.asp?state=CO |archivedate=6 March 2016 }}</ref> The community was named for evergreen trees near the original town site.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dawson|first=John Frank|title=Place names in Colorado: why 700 communities were so named, 150 of Spanish or Indian origin|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015051116740;view=1up;seq=26|publisher=The J. Frank Dawson Publishing Co.|location=Denver, CO|page=20}}</ref>\n\n==Law and government==\nSince Evergreen is an unincorporated area, services usually provided by a city's government are provided by multiple agencies. The county maintains the roads (less State Highway 74), oversees planning and zoning, provides primary and secondary education through its school district and provides law enforcement through its sheriff's office. Evergreen Fire/Rescue provides fire protection and emergency medical response service. Water and sewer services operate under the administration of the Evergreen Metropolitan District.\n\n==Geography==\nEvergreen sits at an elevation of {{convert|7220|ft|m}} in the [[Rocky Mountains]], 19 miles west of [[Denver|Denver, Colorado]].\nEvergreen is located at {{coord|39|38|20|N|105|20|11|W|type:city}} (39.638905, -105.336318).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the CDP has a total area of {{convert|11.6|sqmi|km2}}, of which, {{convert|11.6|sqmi|km2}} of it is land and {{convert|0.1|sqmi|km2}} of it (0.52%) is water.\n\n==Climate==\n{{Weather box\n|location = Evergreen, Colorado (Elevation 7,220ft) \n|single line = Y \n|Jan record high F = 74\n|Feb record high F = 71\n|Mar record high F = 78\n|Apr record high F = 82\n|May record high F = 92\n|Jun record high F = 97\n|Jul record high F = 96\n|Aug record high F = 96\n|Sep record high F = 92\n|Oct record high F = 85\n|Nov record high F = 77\n|Dec record high F = 69\n|year record high F = 97\n|Jan high F = 44.3\n|Feb high F = 45.3\n|Mar high F = 50.1\n|Apr high F = 56.7\n|May high F = 65.0\n|Jun high F = 75.5\n|Jul high F = 81.6\n|Aug high F = 79.5\n|Sep high F = 72.2\n|Oct high F = 62.2\n|Nov high F = 51.0\n|Dec high F = 44.8\n|year high F = 60.7\n|Jan low F = 10.2\n|Feb low F = 12.1\n|Mar low F = 18.5\n|Apr low F = 25.7\n|May low F = 33.9\n|Jun low F = 41.3\n|Jul low F = 47.0\n|Aug low F = 45.5\n|Sep low F = 37.2\n|Oct low F = 27.0\n|Nov low F = 18.2\n|Dec low F = 10.9\n|year low F = 27.3\n|Jan record low F = \u221238\n|Feb record low F = \u221228\n|Mar record low F = \u221218\n|Apr record low F = -9\n|May record low F = 12\n|Jun record low F = 27\n|Jul record low F = 26\n|Aug record low F = 29\n|Sep record low F = 8\n|Oct record low F = -8\n|Nov record low F = \u221215\n|Dec record low F = \u221229\n|year record low F = \u221238\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation inch = 0.55\n|Feb precipitation inch = 0.72\n|Mar precipitation inch = 1.62\n|Apr precipitation inch = 2.18\n|May precipitation inch = 2.55\n|Jun precipitation inch = 2.09\n|Jul precipitation inch = 2.27\n|Aug precipitation inch = 2.26\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.45\n|Oct precipitation inch = 1.26\n|Nov precipitation inch = 0.91\n|Dec precipitation inch = 0.77\n|year precipitation inch = 18.64\n|Jan snow inch = 8.5\n|Feb snow inch = 10.3\n|Mar snow inch = 18.2\n|Apr snow inch = 13.7\n|May snow inch = 3.3\n|Jun snow inch = 0.1\n|Jul snow inch = 0.0\n|Aug snow inch = 0\n|Sep snow inch = 1.4\n|Oct snow inch = 7.2\n|Nov snow inch = 11.6\n|Dec snow inch = 10.4\n|year snow inch = 84.7\n|source 1 = The Western Regional Climate Center<ref name=\"WRCC\">{{cite web\n| url =http://www.wrcc.dri.edu/cgi-bin/cliMAIN.pl?co2790| title =Seasonal Temperature and Precipitation Information | accessdate =November 18, 2013 | publisher =Western Regional Climate Center | language = }}</ref>\n|date=November 2013\n}}\n\n===Major Parks===\n[[File:Evergreen-Lakehouse.jpg|left|thumb|Evergreen lake house in the summer]]\nEvergreen is surrounded by thousands of acres of land in the [[Denver Mountain Parks]] and Jefferson County Open Space park systems. The Denver Mountain Parks in the area are [[Bergen Park]], Corwina Park, [[Dedisse Park]], Dillon Park, [[Fillius Park]], [[O'Fallon Park]] and [[Pence Park]] in Indian Hills. The Jefferson County Open Space Parks are Alderfer/Three Sisters, [[Elk Meadow Park|Elk Meadow]], Lair o' the Bear, and Mount Falcon Park in Indian Hills. [[Hiwan Golf Club]], a country club located just east of [[Bergen Park]], is Evergreen's only country club. Popular both in the summer and the winter, Evergreen Lake and its \"Lake House\" are recreational focal points for the area.\n\n===Transportation===\nThe two major roads in Evergreen are [[Colorado State Highway 74|State Highway 74]] and County Highway 73. Highway 74 runs south from [[Interstate 70 (Colorado)|Interstate 70]] through Bergen Park and northern Evergreen to downtown, then turns east and follows Bear Creek Canyon to its end at [[Colorado State Highway 8|State Highway 8]] near Red Rocks Park. Highway 73 runs south from downtown Evergreen to connect with [[U.S. Route 285 in Colorado|U.S. Highway 285]] in Conifer.\n\nBus service in Evergreen is offered by Denver [[Regional Transportation District]]. [[RTD Bus & Rail|TheRide]] regional routes E and Z run to downtown Denver and there is call-n-Ride curb-to-curb transportation service in town.<ref>[http://www.rtd-denver.com/SpecialRides/call-n-Ride/evergreencnr.htm RTD Evergreen call-n-Ride] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513091006/http://www.rtd-denver.com/SpecialRides/call-n-Ride/evergreencnr.htm |date=2007-05-13 }}.</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 9,216 people, 3,591 households, and 2,689 families residing in the CDP.  The [[population density]] was 795.7 people per square mile (307.3/km<sup>2</sup>).  There were 3,840 housing units at an average density of 331.5 per square mile (128.0/km<sup>2</sup>).  The racial makeup of the CDP was 97.35% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.26% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.36% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.62% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.07% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.25% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.10% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.08% of the population.\n[[File:Downtown Evergreen, Colorado.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Downtown Evergreen]]\nThere were 3,591 households out of which 36.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 65.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 6.5% had a female householder with no husband present, and 25.1% were non-families. 19.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 3.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.56 and the average family size was 2.94.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 25.9% under the age of 18, 4.6% from 18 to 24, 29.6% from 25 to 44, 31.7% from 45 to 64, and 8.2% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females, there were 99.4 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 96.6 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $79,380, and the median income for a family was $88,589. Males had a median income of $62,917 versus $37,392 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $36,654.  About 2.3% of families and 3.0% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 1.3% of those under age 18 and 4.7% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Sites of interest==\n[[File:Sunny Fox.jpg|thumb|A [[red fox]] on the porch of an Evergreen home.]]\nEvergreen Lake, a popular recreation area, was created by damming Bear Creek in 1927. It sits above downtown Evergreen, which includes a mix of historic buildings and local businesses, including the well-known entertainment venue and restaurant The Little Bear.\n\nIn the winter, ice skating is offered at Evergreen Lake. The skating season usually runs from mid-to-late December (approximately Christmas) to late March depending upon ice thickness and weather. Evergreen Lake is the venue of the annual Skate the Lake celebration that takes place on New Year's Eve and the Evergreen Pond Hockey Championship which usually takes place in the first weekend of January.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://drive-smart.org/skate-the-lake/|title=Skate the Lake|date=2013-11-21|newspaper=Drive Smart|access-date=2017-02-22|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>url=https://www.evergreenrecreation.com/Facilities/Evergreen_Lake_House/Evergreen_Pond_Hockey_Championship.htm</ref>\n\nRegistered Historic Places in Evergreen include:\n* [[Bergen Park]]\n* [[Dedisse Park]]\n* [[Evergreen Conference District]]\n* [[Everhardt Ranch]]\n* [[Fillius Park]]\n* [[Hiwan Homestead]]\n* [[Humphrey House (Evergreen, Colorado)|Humphrey House]]\n* [[Corwina Park, O'Fallon Park, Pence Park|O'Fallon Park]]\n* [[Corwina Park, O'Fallon Park, Pence Park|Pence Park]]\n\n==Education==\n{{expand section|date=March 2020}}\nThe entire Evergreen CDP is within the [[Jefferson County Public Schools (Colorado)|Jefferson County Public Schools]] area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/GUBlock/st08_co/place/p0825390_evergreen/DC10BLK_P0825390_000.pdf|title=Evergreen Index Map|publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2020-03-29}} - Pages [https://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/GUBlock/st08_co/place/p0825390_evergreen/DC10BLK_P0825390_001.pdf 1] and [https://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/GUBlock/st08_co/place/p0825390_evergreen/DC10BLK_P0825390_002.pdf 2]</ref> Zoned schools for the CDP include:\n* Zoned elementary schools: Bergen Valley and Wilmot<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B1rGW26Xs8ZMelJ2Q2JaVFdVYms/view|title=Elementary Schools|publisher=[[Jeffco Public Schools]]|accessdate=2020-03-28}} Detail maps: [https://docs.google.com/a/jeffcoschools.us/file/d/0BxRbRgZjmQ8xRmlpNGlYQjJ3d0k/edit Bergen Valley] and [https://docs.google.com/a/jeffcoschools.us/file/d/0BxRbRgZjmQ8xc1pQUWVzQzlYX2M/edit Wilmot]</ref>\n* Evergreen Middle School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B1rGW26Xs8ZMdHZuWW1yZmdzU2s/view|title=Middle Schools|publisher=[[Jeffco Public Schools]]|accessdate=2020-03-28}} - [https://docs.google.com/a/jeffcoschools.us/file/d/0BxRbRgZjmQ8xRnBYMlFKRHlLZ3M/edit Detail map]</ref>\n* [[Evergreen High School (Evergreen, Colorado)|Evergreen High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B1rGW26Xs8ZMUU5DMmNOMTQ4M28/view|title=High Schools|publisher=[[Jeffco Public Schools]]|accessdate=2020-03-28}} - [https://docs.google.com/a/jeffcoschools.us/file/d/0BxRbRgZjmQ8xUmEzbC1FRF9NNDQ/edit Detail map]</ref>\n\nSome other areas with Evergreen addresses to the south fall into the area for [[Conifer High School]]. Most students in the Evergreen area go to Evergreen Middle School.  There are four elementary schools in the Evergreen area; Bergen Meadow, Bergen Valley, Wilmot, and Marshdale Elementary.\n\nResidents with Evergreen addresses west of the Clear Creek County line are served by Clear Creek Schools with students attending King-Murphy Elementary (ranked in the top 1% of elementary schools in Colorado), Clear Creek Middle School, and Clear Creek High School.\n\nPrivate schools in Evergreen include Evergreen Academy, Evergreen Country Day School, Grace Christian School, and Montessori School Of Evergreen.\n\n==Notable residents==\n*[[South Park]] co-creator [[Trey Parker]] graduated from Evergreen High School in 1988.\n*Astronaut [[Jeffrey Ashby]] graduated from Evergreen High School in 1972.\n*[[Willie Nelson]] owned a 44-acre ranch in Evergreen for several years, but sold it in 1991.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1914&dat=19910807&id=az0pAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yGUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3478,1297158</ref>\n*MLB player [[Kevin Kouzmanoff]] grew up in Evergreen and graduated from Evergreen High School in 1999.\n*[[Diane Mott Davidson]], author\n*[[Joanne Greenberg]], author\n*[[Jasmine Cresswell]], romance novelist\n*[[Levi Brackman]], author, rabbi and Jewish writer and thinker\n*[[John Hinckley, Jr.]], shot President Ronald Reagan, lived in Evergreen.<ref>[http://www.law.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/hinckley/hinckleyaccount.html The Trial of John W. Hinckley, Jr.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020803230701/http://www.law.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/hinckley/hinckleyaccount.html |date=2002-08-03 }}, by Doug Linder. 2008.</ref>\n*[[Berkley Breathed]], author\n*[[Gary Hart]], former U.S. senator\n*[[Scott Hamilton (figure skater)|Scott Hamilton]], Olympic medalist\n* [[Noah Hoffman]] (born 1989), American Olympic skier\n* [[Jake Roper]] (born 1987), internet personality\n*[[Nate Dern]] (born 1984), author, comedian\n*[[Peter Scanavino]] (born 1980), actor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/6551/peter-scanavino/|title=Peter Scanavino|website=Broadway.com|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Geography|North America|<!--Northern America-->|United States|Colorado|Mountains}}\n*[[Outline of Colorado]]\n**[[Index of Colorado-related articles]]\n*[[State of Colorado]]\n**[[Colorado cities and towns]]\n***[[Colorado census designated places]]\n**[[Colorado counties]]\n***[[Jefferson County, Colorado]]\n**[[Colorado metropolitan areas]]\n***[[Front Range Urban Corridor]]\n***[[North Central Colorado Urban Area]]\n***[[Denver-Aurora-Boulder, CO Combined Statistical Area]]\n***[[Denver-Aurora-Broomfield, CO Metropolitan Statistical Area]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.evergreenchamber.org/ Evergreen Chamber of Commerce]\n{{Jefferson County, Colorado}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Jefferson County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Denver metropolitan area]]\n", "name_user": "Fleet111", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added info to the school section and a link to The Evergreen Experience which is a comprehensive website dedicated to living in Evergreen Colorado. I am a resident of Evergreen Colorado.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evergreen,_Colorado"}
{"title_page": "Dixon (DJ)", "text_new": "\n\n}}\n\n'''Dixon''' (born '''Steffen Berkhahn'''; 21 December 1975 in [[Anklam]], Germany<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.djhistory.com/interviews/dixon|title=DJ History - interview with Dixon|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628113807/http://www.djhistory.com/interviews/dixon|archive-date=2016-06-28|url-status=dead}}</ref>) is a [[Berlin]]-based artist, best known as a [[house music|house]] and [[techno]] [[DJ]] and [[Record producer|producer]], as well founder of record label Innervisions.  In recent years, he has also made endeavours into fashion and technology, and is the joint owner of club-wear clothing brand Together We Dance Alone. In 2019 he launched an Ibiza residency and digital platform of the same name, Transmoderna. Dixon was voted as the number one DJ on [[Resident Advisor]]'s Top 100 DJ Poll every year from 2013 to the last annual poll in 2016.\n\n== Life and work ==\nBerkhahn grew up in [[East Berlin]] and was aiming for a career as a professional footballer or a long-distance runner, an ambition that was thwarted due to injury.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03s8q79|title=Dixon - Hall Of Fame, Dixon and Emanuel Satie, Pete Tong - BBC Radio 1|website=BBC|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://crackmagazine.net/article/music/dixon/|title=DIXON {{!}} Crack Magazine|newspaper=Crack Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.taz.de/!343545/|title=Die DJs mit der Goldkante|last=Rapp|first=Tobias|newspaper=die tageszeitung|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fr.traxmag.com/article/30158-dixon-et-le-football-une-occasion-ratee|title=Dixon et le football, une occasion rat\u00e9e|newspaper=Trax magazine|language=fr-FR|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s he began DJing under the name Dixon in Berlin clubs such as Turbine, [[Tresor (club)|Tresor]], E-Werk and WMF.<ref name=\":3\" /> For several years he held a weekly residency at WMF with Mitja Prinz, which he describes a key experience in his formative years as a DJ.<ref name=\":0\" /> His residencies at Tresor, WMF and later Weekend Club all involved playing long sets.<ref name=\":0\" /> In a city known in particular for techno music, Dixon established a reputation as a deep house DJ.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/features/2383|title=Innervisions: Lost in a moment|last=Advisor|first=Resident|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pb87CgAAQBAJ&pg=PT175&lpg=PT175&dq=dixon+berkhahn#v=onepage&q=dixon%20berkhahn&f=false|title=Lost and Sound: Berlin, Techno und der Easyjetset|last=Rapp|first=Tobias|date=2012-09-17|publisher=Suhrkamp Verlag|isbn=9783518733950|language=de}}</ref>\n\nDixon's global prominence as a DJ has grown over the years through appearances at clubs and festivals worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/dj/dixon/dates|title=RA: Dixon tour dates|last=Advisor|first=Resident|website=Resident Advisor|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://groove.de/2014/05/09/feature-innervisions-ueber-das-auflegen-groove-147/|title=INNERVISIONS \u00dcber das Auflegen|last=Janson|first=Gerd|date=2014-05-09|website=Groove|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> He was voted No. 1 in [[Resident Advisor]]'s Top 100 DJ Poll in the years 2013, 2014, 2015 and 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/features/1968|title=RA Poll: Top DJs of 2013|date=|publisher=Residentadvisor.net|accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/features/2328|title=RA Poll: Top DJs of 2014|date=|publisher=Residentadvisor.net|accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/features/2571|title=RA Poll: Top DJs of 2015|date=|publisher=Residentadvisor.net|accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Resident Advisor Reveals Its Top 100 DJs of 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/6804505/resident-advisor-top-100-djs-2015|website=www.billboard.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/features/2857|title=RA Poll: Top DJs of 2016|last=Advisor|first=Resident|newspaper=Resident Advisor|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7603851/resident-advisor-top-100-2016-dixon|title=Dixon Tops Resident Advisor's 2016 Top 100 List|newspaper=Billboard|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thump.vice.com/en_ca/article/ra-top-djs-readers-poll-2016-dixon|title=Dixon Tops RA's 2016 Readers Poll for the Fourth Year {{!}} Thump|newspaper=Thump|language=en-CA|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref> In terms of style, German newspaper ''[[Die Welt]]'' credits Dixon with \"bringing back vocals, drama and grand emotions to the dancefloor\" after the electronic dance music scene was dominated by minimal techno for several years.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Vergessen wir, was Montag bis Freitag war|url=https://www.welt.de/kultur/pop/article124699959/Vergessen-wir-was-Montag-bis-Freitag-war.html|website=Die Welt}}</ref> [[Die Tageszeitung]] agrees that Dixon and Innervisions \"changed the sound of Berlin.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nDixon first began record label and A&R work at the [[Sonar Kollektiv|Sonar-Kollektiv]] sublabel Recreation Recordings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cocoon.net/artist/dixon|title=artist {{!}} Dixon {{!}} cocoon.net|website=www.cocoon.net|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref> In 2005 he founded the label Innervisions with Kristian Beyer and [[Frank Wiedemann]] from [[\u00c2me]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thump.vice.com/en_us/article/innervisions-co-founders-me-and-dixon-to-record-b2b-essential-mix-in-april|title=Innervisions Co-founders \u00c2me and Dixon To Record b2b Essential Mix in April {{!}} Thump|newspaper=Thump|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mixmag.net/read/watch-a-documentary-profiling-dixon-and-ames-innervisions-label-news|title=Watch a documentary profiling Dixon and \u00c2me's Innervisions label|newspaper=Mixmag|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref> Initially a sub-label of Sonar Kollektiv, it became independent in 2006.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ibiza-voice.com/story/news/2049|title=Dixon - Sound and InnerVisions|last=Voice|first=Ibiza|date=|website=www.ibiza-voice.com|publisher=|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref> British magazine [[Mixmag]] says the label has had \"an astounding influence on the global house scene.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Essential Innervisions Tracks|url=http://mixmag.net/feature/10-essential-innervisions-tracks|website=www.mixmag.net}}</ref>\n\nAs a producer, Dixon has released several EPs in collaboration with artists such as Georg Levin, [[Derrick Carter]], Henrik Schwarz and \u00c2me.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/4492-Dixon|title=Dixon|website=Discogs|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-64628314.html|title=POP: Minimal ist besser - DER SPIEGEL 12/2009|last=Germany|first=SPIEGEL ONLINE, Hamburg|website=www.spiegel.de|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/43jw/|title=BBC - Music - Review of Wahoo - Take It Personal|last=Patel|first=Amar|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref> Dixon often creates his own edits of other artists' tracks for use in his DJ sets.<ref name=\":1\" /> Some of the most notable of these include his 2017 edit of Depeche Mode's \"Cover Me\" and 2018 edit of \"i used to\" by LCD Soundsystem, both released on [Columbia Records]. \n\nBerkhahn lives with his wife and son in Berlin.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2018, Dixon was added into ''[[Grand Theft Auto Online]]'' as a nightclub DJ as part of the ''After Hours'' DLC.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Donnelly |first1=Joe |title=GTA Online invites real-world DJ Dixon to Los Santos, adds new plane and music |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/gta-online-invites-real-world-dj-dixon-to-los-santos-adds-new-plane-and-music/ |website=PC Gamer |accessdate=7 August 2018 |date=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Together We Dance Alone== \nIn 2017, Dixon branched out from music and started his own fashion label \"Together We Dance Alone\", along with it current creative director, Ana Ofak. The label released its first limited-edition long sleeve in conjunction with designer Kristina Nagel, before aligning with Japanese fashion brand [[Sacai]] to release another long-sleeved style, which was available in Sacai's Tokyo showroom and Together We Dance Alone's [https://togetherwedancealone.com/ webshop]. <ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/lisakocay/2018/08/01/dixon-clothing-label-together-we-dance-alone/#32d632cc1c74</ref>\n\nSince then the brand has teamed up with a number of other designers, and continued to collaborate with [[Sacai]], releasing an additional limited edition printed short sleeve design in December 2019. <ref>https://togetherwedancealone.com/</ref>\n\nAlongside Together We Dance Alone's online store, there are select stores in Los Angeles, Berlin and Paris. <ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/lisakocay/2018/08/01/dixon-clothing-label-together-we-dance-alone/#32d632cc1c74</ref>\n\n==Transmoderna== \nIn the Summer of 2019, Dixon launched the first season of his Ibiza residency, [[Transmoderna]]. The initial season was hosted at Pacha and ran every Friday night for 20 weeks, from May to October. Transmoderna evolved into more than just a club night, in parallel acting as a digital platform to explore boundaries between different spheres of the music, art, fashion, technology and club culture. With particular focus on crossovers between the real and virtual, Transmoderna reached into elements of [[Augmented reality|AR]], launching two of their own [[Instagram]] face filters, created by Johanna Jaskowska. <ref>https://032c.com/the-future-has-expired-dixons-transmoderna-seeks-the-spirit-of-the-present</ref>\n\nTowards the end of the first season, an official Transmoderna [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NOZ0-HmhBXE music video] was released, representing a culmination of the overlapping elements that came together initially to form the overall Transmoderna concept. Soundtracked by [[\u00c2me]] and [[Mathew Jonson]], it brought together visual artists, fashion designers, choreographers, dance performers and programmers, which was then given to an AI to tweak and alter the final product. <ref>https://032c.com/the-future-has-expired-dixons-transmoderna-seeks-the-spirit-of-the-present</ref>\n\nTransmoderna has since been confirmed for a second season, with its venue announced to be moving to [[DC10 (nightclub)|DC10]] in 2020. <ref>https://www.residentadvisor.net/news/71837</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Singles & EPs ===\n\n* 2005: Wahoo presented By Dixon and Georg Levin \u2013 ''Holding You'' ([[Sonar Kollektiv]])\t\n* 2006: Henrik Schwarz / \u00c2me / Dixon feat. Derrick L. Carter \u2013 ''Where We At EP'' (Sonar Kollektiv, Innervisions)\t\n* 2008: Henrik Schwarz / \u00c2me / Dixon \u2013 ''D.P.O.M.B. EP'' (Innervisions)\t\n* 2009: Dixon \u2013 ''Temporary Secretary \u2013 Dixon Edits'' (Innervisions)\t\n* 2010: Henrik Schwarz / \u00c2me / Dixon \u2013 ''A Critical Mass Live EP'' (Innervisions)\n* 2014: [[Guy Gerber]] & Dixon \u2013 ''No Distance EP'' (Rumors)\n\n=== Mixes and compilations ===\n\n* 1999: V.A. \u2013 ''Off Limits'' (Recreation Recordings)\n* 2000: V.A. \u2013 ''Off Limits 2'' (Recreation Recordings)\n* 2001: Dixon and Mitja Prinz \u2013 ''Audio Video Disco'' (WMF Records)\n* 2002: V.A. \u2013 ''Off Limits 3'' (Recreation Recordings)\t\n* 2007: DJ Dixon \u2013 ''Body Language Vol. 4'' ([[Get Physical Music]])\n* 2009: Dixon \u2013 ''Temporary Secretary'' (Innervisions)\n* 2009: Henrik Schwarz / \u00c2me / Dixon \u2013 ''The Grandfather Paradox'' (BBE)\n* 2010: Dixon \u2013 ''Five Years Of Innervisions Compiled & Mixed By Dixon \u00d7 Air'' (Lastrum)\n* 2011: Dixon \u2013 ''Live At Robert Johnson Volume 8'' (Live At Robert Johnson)\n\n=== Remixes (selected) ===\n\n* 2007: [[Tokyo Black Star]] - Still Sequence - Innervisions Version - \u00c2me & Dixon ([[Innervisions_(Label)]])\n* 2007: [[Will Saul]] - Mbira Wahoo - Dixon Remix\n* 2009: [[Martin Iveson|Atjazz]] - Harmony - Dixon\u2019s Late Night Mix (Atjazz Record Company)\n* 2009: The Machine - Fuse - Dixon Remix ([[Innervisions_(Label)]])\n* 2009: Romanthony - The Wanderer - Dixon Edit (Glasgow Underground)\n* 2012: [[Matthew Dekay]], [[Lee Burridge]] - Lost In A Moment - Dixon Rework ([[Innervisions_(Label)]])\n* 2013: [[The xx|The XX]] - Tides - Dixon Remix ([[Young Turks (record label)|Young Turks]])\n* 2013: [[Mano Le Tough]] - Everything You\u2019ve Done Before - Dixon Remix (Permanent Vacation)\n* 2013: [[Mathew Jonson]] - Level 7 - Dixon Remix (Crosstown Rebels)\n* 2014: [[Claude VonStroke]] - Urban Animal - Dixon Dub Mix ([[Dirtybird Records|Dirtybird]])\n* 2014: Joy Wellboy - Before The Sunrise - Dixon Remix ([[BPitch Control|Bpitch Control]])\n* 2015: [[Richie Hawtin|Plastikman]] - EXhale - Dixon\u2019s Just A Different Mixdown Version ([[Mute Records]])\n* 2016: [[Todd Terje]] - Snooze 4 Love - Dixon Remix (Olsen Records)\n* 2017: [[Depeche Mode]] - Cover Me - Dixon Remix ([[Columbia Records]])\n* 2017: [[Chlo\u00e9]] - The Dawn - Dixon Remix (Lumi\u00e8re Noire Records)\n* 2018: [[LCD Soundsystem]] - i used to - dixon retouch ([[Columbia Records]])\n* 2018: [[Radio Slave]] - Trans - Dixon Retouch (Rekids)\n* 2019: [[Kelsey Lu]] - Why Knock For You - Dixon Retouch ([[Columbia Records]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Discogs artist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dixon}}\n[[Category:German DJs]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Berlin]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Anklam]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music DJs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Dixon\n| background       = non_performing_personnel\n| image            = DIXON IMAGe DAVIT 021.jpg\n| landscape        = yes\n| birth_name       = Steffen Berkhahn\n| alias            = Dixon\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1975|12|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Anklam]], [[East Germany]]\n| genre            = [[House music|House]], [[techno]]\n| occupation       = [[DJ]], [[record producer|Producer]], Record Label Founder, Fashion Label Founder\n| years_active     = 1991\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = [[\u00c2me]], [[Recondite]], Marcus Worgull, [[Henrik Schwarz]]\n| Label            = Innervisions, [[Sonar Kollektiv]], [[Get Physical Music]], WMF Records\n}}\n\n'''Dixon''' (born '''Steffen Berkhahn'''; 21 December 1975 in [[Anklam]], Germany<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.djhistory.com/interviews/dixon|title=DJ History - interview with Dixon|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628113807/http://www.djhistory.com/interviews/dixon|archive-date=2016-06-28|url-status=dead}}</ref>) is a [[Berlin]]-based artist, best known as a [[house music|house]] and [[techno]] [[DJ]] and [[Record producer|producer]], as well founder of record label Innervisions.  In recent years, he has also made endeavours into fashion and technology, and is the joint owner of club-wear clothing brand Together We Dance Alone. In 2019 he launched an Ibiza residency and digital platform of the same name, Transmoderna. Dixon was voted as the number one DJ on [[Resident Advisor]]'s Top 100 DJ Poll every year from 2013 to the last annual poll in 2016.\n\n== Life and work ==\nBerkhahn grew up in [[East Berlin]] and was aiming for a career as a professional footballer or a long-distance runner, an ambition that was thwarted due to injury.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03s8q79|title=Dixon - Hall Of Fame, Dixon and Emanuel Satie, Pete Tong - BBC Radio 1|website=BBC|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://crackmagazine.net/article/music/dixon/|title=DIXON {{!}} Crack Magazine|newspaper=Crack Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.taz.de/!343545/|title=Die DJs mit der Goldkante|last=Rapp|first=Tobias|newspaper=die tageszeitung|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fr.traxmag.com/article/30158-dixon-et-le-football-une-occasion-ratee|title=Dixon et le football, une occasion rat\u00e9e|newspaper=Trax magazine|language=fr-FR|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s he began DJing under the name Dixon in Berlin clubs such as Turbine, [[Tresor (club)|Tresor]], E-Werk and WMF.<ref name=\":3\" /> For several years he held a weekly residency at WMF with Mitja Prinz, which he describes a key experience in his formative years as a DJ.<ref name=\":0\" /> His residencies at Tresor, WMF and later Weekend Club all involved playing long sets.<ref name=\":0\" /> In a city known in particular for techno music, Dixon established a reputation as a deep house DJ.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/features/2383|title=Innervisions: Lost in a moment|last=Advisor|first=Resident|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pb87CgAAQBAJ&pg=PT175&lpg=PT175&dq=dixon+berkhahn#v=onepage&q=dixon%20berkhahn&f=false|title=Lost and Sound: Berlin, Techno und der Easyjetset|last=Rapp|first=Tobias|date=2012-09-17|publisher=Suhrkamp Verlag|isbn=9783518733950|language=de}}</ref>\n\nDixon's global prominence as a DJ has grown over the years through appearances at clubs and festivals worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/dj/dixon/dates|title=RA: Dixon tour dates|last=Advisor|first=Resident|website=Resident Advisor|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://groove.de/2014/05/09/feature-innervisions-ueber-das-auflegen-groove-147/|title=INNERVISIONS \u00dcber das Auflegen|last=Janson|first=Gerd|date=2014-05-09|website=Groove|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> He was voted No. 1 in [[Resident Advisor]]'s Top 100 DJ Poll in the years 2013, 2014, 2015 and 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/features/1968|title=RA Poll: Top DJs of 2013|date=|publisher=Residentadvisor.net|accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/features/2328|title=RA Poll: Top DJs of 2014|date=|publisher=Residentadvisor.net|accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/features/2571|title=RA Poll: Top DJs of 2015|date=|publisher=Residentadvisor.net|accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Resident Advisor Reveals Its Top 100 DJs of 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/6804505/resident-advisor-top-100-djs-2015|website=www.billboard.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/features/2857|title=RA Poll: Top DJs of 2016|last=Advisor|first=Resident|newspaper=Resident Advisor|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7603851/resident-advisor-top-100-2016-dixon|title=Dixon Tops Resident Advisor's 2016 Top 100 List|newspaper=Billboard|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thump.vice.com/en_ca/article/ra-top-djs-readers-poll-2016-dixon|title=Dixon Tops RA's 2016 Readers Poll for the Fourth Year {{!}} Thump|newspaper=Thump|language=en-CA|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref> In terms of style, German newspaper ''[[Die Welt]]'' credits Dixon with \"bringing back vocals, drama and grand emotions to the dancefloor\" after the electronic dance music scene was dominated by minimal techno for several years.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Vergessen wir, was Montag bis Freitag war|url=https://www.welt.de/kultur/pop/article124699959/Vergessen-wir-was-Montag-bis-Freitag-war.html|website=Die Welt}}</ref> [[Die Tageszeitung]] agrees that Dixon and Innervisions \"changed the sound of Berlin.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nDixon first began record label and A&R work at the [[Sonar Kollektiv|Sonar-Kollektiv]] sublabel Recreation Recordings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cocoon.net/artist/dixon|title=artist {{!}} Dixon {{!}} cocoon.net|website=www.cocoon.net|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref> In 2005 he founded the label Innervisions with Kristian Beyer and [[Frank Wiedemann]] from [[\u00c2me]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thump.vice.com/en_us/article/innervisions-co-founders-me-and-dixon-to-record-b2b-essential-mix-in-april|title=Innervisions Co-founders \u00c2me and Dixon To Record b2b Essential Mix in April {{!}} Thump|newspaper=Thump|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mixmag.net/read/watch-a-documentary-profiling-dixon-and-ames-innervisions-label-news|title=Watch a documentary profiling Dixon and \u00c2me's Innervisions label|newspaper=Mixmag|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref> Initially a sub-label of Sonar Kollektiv, it became independent in 2006.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ibiza-voice.com/story/news/2049|title=Dixon - Sound and InnerVisions|last=Voice|first=Ibiza|date=|website=www.ibiza-voice.com|publisher=|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref> British magazine [[Mixmag]] says the label has had \"an astounding influence on the global house scene.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Essential Innervisions Tracks|url=http://mixmag.net/feature/10-essential-innervisions-tracks|website=www.mixmag.net}}</ref>\n\nAs a producer, Dixon has released several EPs in collaboration with artists such as Georg Levin, [[Derrick Carter]], Henrik Schwarz and \u00c2me.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/4492-Dixon|title=Dixon|website=Discogs|access-date=2016-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-64628314.html|title=POP: Minimal ist besser - DER SPIEGEL 12/2009|last=Germany|first=SPIEGEL ONLINE, Hamburg|website=www.spiegel.de|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/43jw/|title=BBC - Music - Review of Wahoo - Take It Personal|last=Patel|first=Amar|access-date=2016-12-15}}</ref> Dixon often creates his own edits of other artists' tracks for use in his DJ sets.<ref name=\":1\" /> Some of the most notable of these include his 2017 edit of Depeche Mode's \"Cover Me\" and 2018 edit of \"i used to\" by LCD Soundsystem, both released on [Columbia Records]. \n\nBerkhahn lives with his wife and son in Berlin.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2018, Dixon was added into ''[[Grand Theft Auto Online]]'' as a nightclub DJ as part of the ''After Hours'' DLC.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Donnelly |first1=Joe |title=GTA Online invites real-world DJ Dixon to Los Santos, adds new plane and music |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/gta-online-invites-real-world-dj-dixon-to-los-santos-adds-new-plane-and-music/ |website=PC Gamer |accessdate=7 August 2018 |date=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Together We Dance Alone== \nIn 2017, Dixon branched out from music and started his own fashion label \"Together We Dance Alone\", along with it current creative director, Ana Ofak. The label released its first limited-edition long sleeve in conjunction with designer Kristina Nagel, before aligning with Japanese fashion brand [[Sacai]] to release another long-sleeved style, which was available in Sacai's Tokyo showroom and Together We Dance Alone's [https://togetherwedancealone.com/ webshop]. <ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/lisakocay/2018/08/01/dixon-clothing-label-together-we-dance-alone/#32d632cc1c74</ref>\n\nSince then the brand has teamed up with a number of other designers, and continued to collaborate with [[Sacai]], releasing an additional limited edition printed short sleeve design in December 2019. <ref>https://togetherwedancealone.com/</ref>\n\nAlongside Together We Dance Alone's online store, there are select stores in Los Angeles, Berlin and Paris. <ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/lisakocay/2018/08/01/dixon-clothing-label-together-we-dance-alone/#32d632cc1c74</ref>\n\n==Transmoderna== \nIn the Summer of 2019, Dixon launched the first season of his Ibiza residency, [[Transmoderna]]. The initial season was hosted at Pacha and ran every Friday night for 20 weeks, from May to October. Transmoderna evolved into more than just a club night, in parallel acting as a digital platform to explore boundaries between different spheres of the music, art, fashion, technology and club culture. With particular focus on crossovers between the real and virtual, Transmoderna reached into elements of [[Augmented reality|AR]], launching two of their own [[Instagram]] face filters, created by Johanna Jaskowska. <ref>https://032c.com/the-future-has-expired-dixons-transmoderna-seeks-the-spirit-of-the-present</ref>\n\nTowards the end of the first season, an official Transmoderna [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NOZ0-HmhBXE music video] was released, representing a culmination of the overlapping elements that came together initially to form the overall Transmoderna concept. Soundtracked by [[\u00c2me]] and [[Mathew Jonson]], it brought together visual artists, fashion designers, choreographers, dance performers and programmers, which was then given to an AI to tweak and alter the final product. <ref>https://032c.com/the-future-has-expired-dixons-transmoderna-seeks-the-spirit-of-the-present</ref>\n\nTransmoderna has since been confirmed for a second season, with its venue announced to be moving to [[DC10 (nightclub)|DC10]] in 2020. <ref>https://www.residentadvisor.net/news/71837</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Singles & EPs ===\n\n* 2005: Wahoo presented By Dixon and Georg Levin \u2013 ''Holding You'' ([[Sonar Kollektiv]])\t\n* 2006: Henrik Schwarz / \u00c2me / Dixon feat. Derrick L. Carter \u2013 ''Where We At EP'' (Sonar Kollektiv, Innervisions)\t\n* 2008: Henrik Schwarz / \u00c2me / Dixon \u2013 ''D.P.O.M.B. EP'' (Innervisions)\t\n* 2009: Dixon \u2013 ''Temporary Secretary \u2013 Dixon Edits'' (Innervisions)\t\n* 2010: Henrik Schwarz / \u00c2me / Dixon \u2013 ''A Critical Mass Live EP'' (Innervisions)\n* 2014: [[Guy Gerber]] & Dixon \u2013 ''No Distance EP'' (Rumors)\n\n=== Mixes and compilations ===\n\n* 1999: V.A. \u2013 ''Off Limits'' (Recreation Recordings)\n* 2000: V.A. \u2013 ''Off Limits 2'' (Recreation Recordings)\n* 2001: Dixon and Mitja Prinz \u2013 ''Audio Video Disco'' (WMF Records)\n* 2002: V.A. \u2013 ''Off Limits 3'' (Recreation Recordings)\t\n* 2007: DJ Dixon \u2013 ''Body Language Vol. 4'' ([[Get Physical Music]])\n* 2009: Dixon \u2013 ''Temporary Secretary'' (Innervisions)\n* 2009: Henrik Schwarz / \u00c2me / Dixon \u2013 ''The Grandfather Paradox'' (BBE)\n* 2010: Dixon \u2013 ''Five Years Of Innervisions Compiled & Mixed By Dixon \u00d7 Air'' (Lastrum)\n* 2011: Dixon \u2013 ''Live At Robert Johnson Volume 8'' (Live At Robert Johnson)\n\n=== Remixes (selected) ===\n\n* 2007: [[Tokyo Black Star]] - Still Sequence - Innervisions Version - \u00c2me & Dixon ([[Innervisions_(Label)]])\n* 2007: [[Will Saul]] - Mbira Wahoo - Dixon Remix\n* 2009: [[Martin Iveson|Atjazz]] - Harmony - Dixon\u2019s Late Night Mix (Atjazz Record Company)\n* 2009: The Machine - Fuse - Dixon Remix ([[Innervisions_(Label)]])\n* 2009: Romanthony - The Wanderer - Dixon Edit (Glasgow Underground)\n* 2012: [[Matthew Dekay]], [[Lee Burridge]] - Lost In A Moment - Dixon Rework ([[Innervisions_(Label)]])\n* 2013: [[The xx|The XX]] - Tides - Dixon Remix ([[Young Turks (record label)|Young Turks]])\n* 2013: [[Mano Le Tough]] - Everything You\u2019ve Done Before - Dixon Remix (Permanent Vacation)\n* 2013: [[Mathew Jonson]] - Level 7 - Dixon Remix (Crosstown Rebels)\n* 2014: [[Claude VonStroke]] - Urban Animal - Dixon Dub Mix ([[Dirtybird Records|Dirtybird]])\n* 2014: Joy Wellboy - Before The Sunrise - Dixon Remix ([[BPitch Control|Bpitch Control]])\n* 2015: [[Richie Hawtin|Plastikman]] - EXhale - Dixon\u2019s Just A Different Mixdown Version ([[Mute Records]])\n* 2016: [[Todd Terje]] - Snooze 4 Love - Dixon Remix (Olsen Records)\n* 2017: [[Depeche Mode]] - Cover Me - Dixon Remix ([[Columbia Records]])\n* 2017: [[Chlo\u00e9]] - The Dawn - Dixon Remix (Lumi\u00e8re Noire Records)\n* 2018: [[LCD Soundsystem]] - i used to - dixon retouch ([[Columbia Records]])\n* 2018: [[Radio Slave]] - Trans - Dixon Retouch (Rekids)\n* 2019: [[Kelsey Lu]] - Why Knock For You - Dixon Retouch ([[Columbia Records]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Discogs artist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dixon}}\n[[Category:German DJs]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Berlin]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Anklam]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music DJs]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:d841:b900:d44b:5d3d:ee21:50d9", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dixon_(DJ)"}
{"title_page": "MDN Web Docs", "text_new": "{{short description|Cross-browser documentation center on web technologies}}\n{{update|date=December 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox website\n| name = MDN Web Docs\n| logo = MDN Web Docs.svg\n| logo_alt = \n| screenshot = \n| collapsetext = <!-- collapsible area's heading (default \"Screenshot\"); omit/leave blank if collapsible not set -->\n| background = <!-- for collapsetext heading; default grey (gainsboro) -->\n| screenshot_size = \n| screenshot_alt = \n| caption = \n| url = {{URL|https://developer.mozilla.org/}}\n| areas = \n| offices = \n| commercial = No\n| type = [[Wiki]]\n| registration = Optional, required to edit content\n| language = more than 25 languages\n| num_users = \n| content_license = [[CC-BY-SA]] v2.5+ et al.\n| programming_language = [[Python (programming language)|Python]]\n| owner = [[Mozilla]]\n| author = <!-- or: creator / authors / creators -->\n| editor = <!-- or: | editors = -->\n| launch_date = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2005}}\n| revenue = \n| current_status = Online\n}}\n\n'''MDN Web Docs''', previously '''Mozilla Developer Network''' and formerly '''Mozilla Developer Center''', is the official [[Mozilla]] [[website]] for development documentation of web standards and Mozilla projects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sitepoint.com/devmo/|title=The Mozilla Developer Center|first=Simon|last=Willison|authorlink=Simon Willison|publisher=[[SitePoint]]|date=2005-09-15|accessdate=2012-08-19}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nMDN Web Docs is a resource for developers, maintained by the community of developers and technical writers and hosting many documents on a wide variety of subjects, such as: [[HTML5]], [[JavaScript]], [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS]], [[Web API]]<nowiki/>s, [[Django (web framework)|Django]], [[Node.js]], [[WebExtension]]s and [[MathML]]. For mobile web developers, MDN provides documentation on subjects such as building an HTML5 mobile app, building a mobile add-on, and location-aware apps.<ref>[https://hacks.mozilla.org/2012/12/ten-things-developers-should-know-about-the-mozilla-developer-network-mdn/ Ten Things Developers should know about the Mozilla Developer Network (MDN)]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe project (originally called Mozilla Developer Center) was started in 2005, and initially led by [[Mozilla Corporation]] employee Deb Richardson in 2005. Documentation efforts have been led by Eric Shepherd since 2006.<ref name=\"MitchellBlog\" />\n\nThe initial content for the website was provided by [[DevEdge]], for which the Mozilla Foundation was granted a license by [[AOL]].<ref name=\"MDCAbout\">{{cite web|url=https://developer.mozilla.org/Project:En/About|title=About|accessdate=2009-01-30|publisher=Mozilla Developer Center|archiveurl=https://developer.mozilla.org/index.php?title=Project:En/About&revision=62|archivedate=2007-10-20}}</ref><ref name=\"MitchellBlog\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.lizardwrangler.com/2005/02/23/devmo-and-devedge-updates/|title=DevMo and DevEdge updates|author=Mitchell Baker|date=2005-02-23|accessdate=2008-05-31}}</ref> The site now contains a mix of content migrated from DevEdge and mozilla.org, as well as original and more up-to-date content.<ref name=\"MDCDevEdge\">{{cite web|url=https://developer.mozilla.org/Project:En/DevEdge|title=DevEdge|publisher=Mozilla Developer Center|accessdate=2009-01-30|archiveurl=https://developer.mozilla.org/index.php?title=Project:En/DevEdge&revision=26|archivedate=2007-10-26}}</ref><ref name=\"DriaDevedge-temp\">{{cite web|url=http://groups.google.com/group/mozilla.dev.mdc/browse_thread/thread/d8cdf5d09f1544d6/1b99a30a311ad11b?lnk=st&q=#1b99a30a311ad11b|title=Digging through the DevEdge archives|author=Deb Richardson|date=2006-02-10|accessdate=2008-05-31|work=mozilla.dev.mdc|publisher=Google Groups}}</ref> Documentation was also migrated from XULPlanet.com.\n\nMDN has a discussion forum and an [[IRC]] channel #mdn on the Mozilla IRC Network. MDN is funded by the Mozilla Corporation with servers and employees.\n\nWith the Oct 3, 2016 release, [[Brave (web browser)|Brave]] features Mozilla Developer Network as one of its default search engines options.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/brave/browser-laptop/releases/tag/v0.12.3dev|title=Brave Browser 0.12.3 Release Note|website=Github|accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, MDN Web Docs became the unified documentation of web technology for Google, Samsung, Microsoft, and Mozilla.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blog.chromium.org/2017/10/building-unified-documentation-for-web.html |title=Building unified documentation for the web |date=2017-10-18 |website=Chromium Blog |first=Dru |last=Knox}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/developers-rejoice-microsoft-google-mozilla-are-putting-all-their-web-api-docs-in-one-place/ |title=Developers rejoice: Microsoft, Google, Mozilla are putting all their web API docs in one place |first=Liam |last=Tung |date=2017-10-19 |website=[[ZDNet]]}}</ref> Microsoft started redirecting pages from MSDN to MDN.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.windows.com/msedgedev/2017/10/18/documenting-web-together-mdn-web-docs/ |title=Documenting the Web together |date=2017-10-18 |website=Windows Blogs |author=Erika Doyle Navara}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Mozilla started a Beta of a rewrite MDN Web Docs site for readers in [[React (JavaScript library)|React]] (instead of [[jQuery]]). Contributors can edit the site contents using the old editor, which is still supported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hub.packtpub.com/mozillas-mdn-web-docs-gets-new-react-powered-frontend-which-is-now-in-beta/|title=Mozilla's MDN Web Docs gets new React-powered frontend, which is now in Beta|last=R|first=Bhagyashree|date=2019-07-17|website=Packt Hub|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}<br />{{Mozilla community}}\n\n[[Category:Mozilla]]\n[[Category:Creative Commons-licensed websites]]\n[[Category:Computing websites]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Wikis about programming]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cross-browser documentation center on web technologies}}\n{{update|date=December 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox website\n| name = MDN Web Docs\n| logo = MDN Web Docs.svg\n| logo_alt = \n| screenshot = \n| collapsetext = <!-- collapsible area's heading (default \"Screenshot\"); omit/leave blank if collapsible not set -->\n| background = <!-- for collapsetext heading; default grey (gainsboro) -->\n| screenshot_size = \n| screenshot_alt = \n| caption = \n| url = {{URL|https://developer.mozilla.org/}}\n| areas = \n| offices = \n| commercial = No\n| type = [[Wiki]]\n| registration = Optional, required to edit content\n| language = more than 25 languages\n| num_users = \n| content_license = [[CC-BY-SA]] v2.5+ et al.\n| programming_language = [[Python (programming language)|Python]]\n| owner = [[Mozilla]]\n| author = <!-- or: creator / authors / creators -->\n| editor = <!-- or: | editors = -->\n| launch_date = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2005}}\n| revenue = \n| current_status = Online\n}}\n\n'''MDN Web Docs''', previously '''Mozilla Developer Network''' and formerly '''Mozilla Developer Center''', is the official [[Mozilla]] [[website]] for development documentation of web standards and Mozilla projects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sitepoint.com/devmo/|title=The Mozilla Developer Center|first=Simon|last=Willison|authorlink=Simon Willison|publisher=[[SitePoint]]|date=2005-09-15|accessdate=2012-08-19}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nMDN Web Docs is a resource for developers, maintained by the community of developers and technical writers and hosting many documents on a wide variety of subjects, such as: [[HTML5]], [[JavaScript]], [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS]], [[Web API]]<nowiki/>s, [[Django (web framework)|Django]], [[Node.js]], [[WebExtension]]s and [[MathML]]. For mobile web developers, MDN provides documentation on subjects such as building an HTML5 mobile app, building a mobile add-on, and location-aware apps.<ref>[https://hacks.mozilla.org/2012/12/ten-things-developers-should-know-about-the-mozilla-developer-network-mdn/ Ten Things Developers should know about the Mozilla Developer Network (MDN)]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe project (originally called Mozilla Developer Center) was started in 2005, and initially led by [[Mozilla Corporation]] employee Deb Richardson in 2005. Documentation efforts have been led by Eric Shepherd since 2006.<ref name=\"MitchellBlog\" />\n\nThe initial content for the website was provided by [[DevEdge]], for which the Mozilla Foundation was granted a license by [[AOL]].<ref name=\"MDCAbout\">{{cite web|url=https://developer.mozilla.org/Project:En/About|title=About|accessdate=2009-01-30|publisher=Mozilla Developer Center|archiveurl=https://developer.mozilla.org/index.php?title=Project:En/About&revision=62|archivedate=2007-10-20}}</ref><ref name=\"MitchellBlog\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.lizardwrangler.com/2005/02/23/devmo-and-devedge-updates/|title=DevMo and DevEdge updates|author=Mitchell Baker|date=2005-02-23|accessdate=2008-05-31}}</ref> The site now contains a mix of content migrated from DevEdge and mozilla.org, as well as original and more up-to-date content.<ref name=\"MDCDevEdge\">{{cite web|url=https://developer.mozilla.org/Project:En/DevEdge|title=DevEdge|publisher=Mozilla Developer Center|accessdate=2009-01-30|archiveurl=https://developer.mozilla.org/index.php?title=Project:En/DevEdge&revision=26|archivedate=2007-10-26}}</ref><ref name=\"DriaDevedge-temp\">{{cite web|url=http://groups.google.com/group/mozilla.dev.mdc/browse_thread/thread/d8cdf5d09f1544d6/1b99a30a311ad11b?lnk=st&q=#1b99a30a311ad11b|title=Digging through the DevEdge archives|author=Deb Richardson|date=2006-02-10|accessdate=2008-05-31|work=mozilla.dev.mdc|publisher=Google Groups}}</ref> Documentation was also migrated from XULPlanet.com.\n\nMDN has a discussion forum and an [[IRC]] channel #mdn on the Mozilla IRC Network. MDN is funded by the Mozilla Corporation with servers and employees.\n\nWith the Oct 3, 2016 release, [[Brave (web browser)|Brave]] features Mozilla Developer Network as one of its default search engines options.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/brave/browser-laptop/releases/tag/v0.12.3dev|title=Brave Browser 0.12.3 Release Note|website=Github|accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, MDN Web Docs became the unified documentation of web technology for Google, Samsung, Microsoft, and Mozilla.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blog.chromium.org/2017/10/building-unified-documentation-for-web.html |title=Building unified documentation for the web |date=2017-10-18 |website=Chromium Blog |first=Dru |last=Knox}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/developers-rejoice-microsoft-google-mozilla-are-putting-all-their-web-api-docs-in-one-place/ |title=Developers rejoice: Microsoft, Google, Mozilla are putting all their web API docs in one place |first=Liam |last=Tung |date=2017-10-19 |website=[[ZDNet]]}}</ref> Microsoft started redirecting pages from MSDN to MDN.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.windows.com/msedgedev/2017/10/18/documenting-web-together-mdn-web-docs/ |title=Documenting the Web together |date=2017-10-18 |website=Windows Blogs |author=Erika Doyle Navara}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Mozilla started a Beta of a rewrite MDN Web Docs site for readers in [[React (JavaScript library)|React]] (instead of [[jQuery]]). Contributors can edit the site contents using the old editor, which is still supported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hub.packtpub.com/mozillas-mdn-web-docs-gets-new-react-powered-frontend-which-is-now-in-beta/|title=Mozilla's MDN Web Docs gets new React-powered frontend, which is now in Beta|last=R|first=Bhagyashree|date=2019-07-17|website=Packt Hub|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}<br />{{Mozilla community}}\n\n[[Category:Mozilla]]\n[[Category:Creative Commons-licensed websites]]\n[[Category:Computing websites]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Wikis about programming]]\n", "name_user": "Sebastian Hudak", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:added comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MDN_Web_Docs"}
{"title_page": "Joseph Stefano", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Joseph Stefano\n| image = Joseph Stefano.jpg\n| birthname = Joseph William Stefano\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1922|5|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2006|8|25|1922|5|5}}\n| death_place = [[Thousand Oaks, California]]\n| spouse = Marilyn Epstein (1954\u20132006)\n| occupation = Screenwriter, producer, director\n}}\n\n'''Joseph William Stefano''' (May 5, 1922 \u2013 August 25, 2006) was an [[United States|American]] [[screenwriter]], best known for adapting [[Robert Bloch]]'s novel as the script for [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s film ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'', and for being the producer and co-writer of the original [[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|''The Outer Limits'']] TV series.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Joseph Stefano, 84, Screenwriter for \u2018Psycho\u2019 and Television, Dies|date=2006-08-31|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/31/obituaries/31stefano.html?pagewanted=print&_r=0}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/29/AR2006082901421.html|last=Bernstein|first=Adam|date=2006-08-30|title=Joseph Stefano; Key Writer for 'Psycho'|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nStefano was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. As a teenager, Stefano was so keen to become an actor that he dropped out of high school two weeks before graduation and traveled to [[New York City]]. In Manhattan he adopted the stage name Jerry Stevens.\n\nStefano's initial career was as a composer of [[pop music]] in the 1940s, writing songs for Las Vegas showman [[Donn Arden]]. In possession of a large collection of sheet music, he once spent five hours challenging pianist [[Michael Feinstein]] on names of obscure [[Tin Pan Alley]] songs.\n\n==Career as screenwriter, producer and director==\nStefano began writing movie scripts in the late 1950s, firstly for [[Martin Ritt]] with ''[[The Black Orchid (film)|The Black Orchid]]'' (1959); his father was a tailor, and his mother made silk flowers and this was an influence on the screenplay.\n\nStefano was commissioned by [[Alfred Hitchcock]] to adapt [[Robert Bloch]]'s novel ''[[Psycho (novel)|Psycho]]'' (1960) for the screen. His work was recognized by the [[Mystery Writers of America]] when he was given a 1961 [[Edgar Award]], for Best Motion Picture Screenplay. Stefano appears briefly onscreen, discussing Bloch's utilization of the basis of the character Norman Bates in the crimes of [[serial killer]] [[Ed Gein]], in the documentary \"Ed Gein: The Ghoul of Plainfield\", which can be found on Disc 2 of the DVD release of the remake of ''[[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre (2003 film)|The Texas Chainsaw Massacre]]'' (2003).\n\nStefano was also offered the job of scripting Hitchcock's ''[[The Birds (film)|The Birds]]'' (1963) and ''[[Marnie (film)|Marnie]]'' (1964), but was already committed to produce and write for his friend [[Leslie Stevens]]' [[science fiction television]] anthology series ''[[The Outer Limits (1963 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]''. Both Stefano and Stevens were involved only during the first season of the show. In the book ''[https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0983205604 Writing with Hitchcock]'', Stefano said that Hitchcock held a grudge over his being unavailable to write the screenplay for ''Marnie''.\n\nAfter leaving the series due to network interference and exhaustion, Stefano wrote, produced and directed ''[[The Ghost of Sierra de Cobre]]'' (1964; aka ''The Haunted''), a film utilizing many of the crew responsible for ''The Outer Limits''. The [[thriller film|thriller]] ''[[Eye of the Cat]]'' (1969) and the [[comedy film|comedy]] ''Futz'' (1969) were Stefano's last big-screen jobs for many years. Throughout the 1970s, he wrote many [[television film]]s such as ''[[Revenge!]]'' (1971), ''[[A Death of Innocence]]'' (1971), ''[[Home for the Holidays (1972 film)|Home for the Holidays]]'' (1972), ''[[Live Again, Die Again]]'' (1974), ''Aloha Means Goodbye'' (1974) and ''[[Snowbeast]]'' (1977). Stefano also wrote one episode for the first season of ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'' (1988) entitled \"[[Skin of Evil]]\". Stefano was one of the Guests of Honor at the 1974 NY Telefantasy Convention (along with [[Noel Neill]], Jim Danforth and William Tuttle), and spent hours signing autographs for hundreds of ''Outer Limits'' fans. At the show, he expressed his surprise that so many people still remembered the series almost a decade after its cancellation.\n\nIn 1990, he revisited the characters from ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' with the TV movie script for the [[prequel]], in what he believed had become an increasingly disappointing series of films. ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]'' (1990) posits the origins of [[Norman Bates]]' destructive mother-love, featuring [[Olivia Hussey]] as Mrs. Bates. Stefano wrote and executive produced the [[Al Pacino]] [[drama]] ''[[Two Bits]]'' (1995), a personal project that fared poorly at the box-office and with critics, leaving Stefano less than enthusiastic about continuing to write for modern Hollywood. [[Gus Van Sant]]'s remake of ''[[Psycho (1998 film)|Psycho]]'' (1998) followed Stefano's script punctiliously, and in the biopic ''[[Hitchcock (film)|Hitchcock]]'' (2012), about the making of ''Psycho,'' he is portrayed by [[Ralph Macchio]].\n\nStefano died of a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] at [[Los Robles Hospital]] in [[Thousand Oaks, California]], in 2006.\n\n==''The Outer Limits''==\nStefano was a producer for the first season of ''The Outer Limits'' and wrote a total of 12 episodes. They are:\n*\"[[Nightmare (1963 The Outer Limits)|Nightmare]]\"\n*\"[[It Crawled Out of the Woodwork]]\"\n*\"[[The Zanti Misfits]]\"\n*\"[[The Mice (The Outer Limits)|The Mice]]\" (teleplay)\n*\"[[Don't Open Till Doomsday]]\"\n*\"[[The Invisibles (The Outer Limits)|The Invisibles]]\"\n*\"[[The Bellero Shield]]\" (story & teleplay)\n*\"[[Moonstone (The Outer Limits)|Moonstone]]\" (story)\n*\"[[Fun and Games (The Outer Limits)|Fun and Games]]\" (teleplay)\n*\"[[A Feasibility Study]]\"\n*\"[[The Chameleon (The Outer Limits)|The Chameleon]]\" (story)\n*\"[[The Forms of Things Unknown]]\"\nThe last episode was originally a pilot for a proposed TV series called ''The Unknown'', but after ABC rejected it, Stefano reworked it as the season one finale.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! [[Screenwriter|Writer]] !! [[Film producer|Producer]] !! Notes\n|-\n| 1958 || ''[[Anna of Brooklyn]]'' ||{{yes}}|| || Co-writer with [[Ettore Margadonna]], Luciana Corda\n|-\n| 1959 || ''[[The Black Orchid (film)|The Black Orchid]]'' ||{{yes}}|| ||\n|-\n| 1960 || ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' ||{{yes}}|| || \n|-\n| 1961 || ''[[The Naked Edge]]'' ||{{yes}}|| || \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1969 || ''[[Eye of the Cat]]'' ||{{yes}}|| ||\n|-\n| ''Futz'' ||{{yes}}|| || \n|-\n| 1987 || ''[[The Kindred (film)|The Kindred]]'' ||{{yes}}|| || Co-writer with [[Stephen Carpenter (writer)|Stephen Carpenter]], [[Jeffrey Obrow]], [[John Penney]], Earl Ghaffari\n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[Blackout (1988 film)|Blackout]]'' ||{{yes}}||{{yes}}|| Co-writer with Laura Ferguson\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Two Bits]]'' ||{{yes}}|| ||\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Psycho (1998 film)|Psycho]]'' ||{{yes}}|| || Remake of 1960 film based on Stefano's screenplay\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! [[Screenwriter|Writer]] !! [[Television director|Director]] !! [[Television producer|Producer]] !! Notes\n|-\n| 1958 || ''[[Playhouse 90]]'' || {{yes}}|| || || Episode: \"Made in Japan\" (story only)\n|-\n| 1959 || ''[[General Electric Theater]]'' ||{{yes}}|| || || Episode: \"Hitler's Secret\"<br>Episode: \"The Committeeman\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1960 || ''[[Startime (TV series)|Startime]]'' ||{{yes}}|| || || Episode: \"The Young Juggler\"\n|-\n| ''[[The Detectives (1959 