{"title_page": "KBVU (TV)", "text_new": "{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = KBVU<br>''([[Broadcast relay station#Semi-satellites|semi-satellite]] of [[KCVU]],<br>[[Paradise, California|Paradise]]/[[Chico, California|Chico]]/[[Redding, California]])''\n| station_logo             = KBVU Fox 28 logo.png\n| location                 = [[Eureka, California]]\n| country                  = [[United States]]\n| city                     = \n| station_branding         = Fox 28 ''(general)''<br>North Coast News ''(newscasts)''\n| station_slogan           = \n| digital                  = 28 ([[Ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 28 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = '''28.1:''' [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]<br>'''28.2:''' [[Cozi TV]]\n| owner                    = [[Cunningham Broadcasting]]\n| licensee                 = Eureka (KBVU-TV) Licensee, Inc.\n| operator                 = [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]]\n| founded                  = July 10, 1991\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1994|7|20|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''B'''est '''VU''' (as in \"view\")<br>or<br>possible rhyming variations of San Francisco Fox affiliate [[KTVU]])\n| sister_stations          = [[KAEF-TV]]\n| former_callsigns         = KZJA ([[Construction permit#Broadcasting|CP]])\n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br>29 (UHF, 1994\u20132009)\n| former_affiliations      = '''Both secondary:'''<br>[[UPN]] (1995\u20131997)<br>[[The WB]] (1995\u20131998)\n| effective_radiated_power = 50 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|513|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = 58618\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|40|43|41.9|N|123|58|21.4|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = \n}}\n\n'''KBVU''', [[Virtual channel|virtual]] and [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[Digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 28, is a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]-[[Network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Eureka, California]], United States. Owned by [[Cunningham Broadcasting]], it is operated under a [[shared services agreement]] by the [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]], making it a [[sister station]] to [[Arcata, California|Arcata]]-licensed [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate [[KAEF-TV]] (channel 23).  It is also sister to two [[Low-power broadcasting#Television|low-power]] stations: dual [[The CW|CW]]/[[MyNetworkTV]] affiliate [[KECA-LD]] (channel 29), and [[Univision]] affiliate [[KEUV-LP]] ([[analog television|analog]] channel 31). The four stations share studios on Sixth Street in downtown Eureka; KBVU's transmitter is located along Barry Road southeast of Eureka.\n\nA [[Master control]] and some internal operations are based at the shared studios of KCVU and LMA partner [[KRCR-TV]] on Auditorium Drive in Redding.\n\n==History==\nThe station signed on the air as a Fox affiliate on July 20, 1994, replacing two satellite stations of [[KRCR-TV]] which broadcast both ABC and Fox programming. Prior to the launch of the station, the network's programming was only available via [[KAEF]] or [[KQSL|KFWU]] (which both carried the network as a secondary affiliation), while out-of-market affiliates [[KTVU]] and [[KTXL-TV]] were imported by some cable providers. \n\nOn April 21, 2017, [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] purchased KBVU as part of a four-station deal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Houston|first1=Will|title=Media giant Sinclair Broadcast Group to buy four Eureka stations|url=http://www.times-standard.com/article/NJ/20170421/NEWS/170429975|accessdate=10 July 2017|date=4 April 2017}}</ref> The sale was completed on September 1.<ref>[http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/prefill_and_display.pl?Application_id=1765804&Service=DT&Form_id=905&Facility_id=58618 Consummation Notice], ''CDBS Public Access'', [[Federal Communications Commission]], Retrieved 6 September 2017.</ref>\n\n==Digital television==\n\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>[http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=KBVU#station RabbitEars TV Query for KBVU]</ref>\n|-\n| 28.1 || [[720p]] || [[16:9]] || KBVU-DT || Main KBVU programming / [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n|-\n| 28.2 || rowspan=3|[[480i]] || rowspan=3|[[4:3]] || COMET || [[Comet (TV network)|Comet]]\n|-\n| 28.3 || CHARGE || [[Charge! (TV network)|Charge!]]\n|-\n| 28.4 || STADIUM || [[Stadium (sports network)|Stadium]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nKBVU shut down its analog signal, over [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 29, on December 22, 2008, along with KCVU, due to lack of funding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and the Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=2012-03-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archivedate=2013-08-29 }}</ref> The station's digital signal broadcasts on its pre-transition UHF channel 28.\n\n==Newscasts==\nKBVU currently airs 2\u00bd hours of newscasts each week, all on weeknights at 10 p.m., as ''North Coast News on KBVU Fox 28 at 10''. The newscasts are produced by sister station KAEF.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Eureka TV}}\n{{Fox California}}\n{{SBGI}}\n\n[[Category:Fox network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Cozi TV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1994]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Eureka, California|BVU (TV)]]\n[[Category:Sinclair Broadcast Group]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = KBVU<br>''([[Broadcast relay station#Semi-satellites|semi-satellite]] of [[KCVU]],<br>[[Paradise, California|Paradise]]/[[Chico, California|Chico]]/[[Redding, California]])''\n| station_logo             = KBVU Fox 28 logo.png\n| location                 = [[Eureka, California]]\n| country                  = [[United States]]\n| city                     = \n| station_branding         = Fox 28 ''(general)''<br>North Coast News ''(newscasts)''\n| station_slogan           = \n| digital                  = 28 ([[Ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 28 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = '''28.1:''' [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]<br>'''28.2:''' [[Cozi TV]]\n| owner                    = [[Cunningham Broadcasting]]\n| licensee                 = Eureka (KBVU-TV) Licensee, Inc.\n| operator                 = [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]]\n| founded                  = July 10, 1991\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1994|7|20|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''B'''est '''VU''' (as in \"view\")<br>or<br>possible rhyming variations of San Francisco Fox affiliate [[KTVU]])\n| sister_stations          = [[KAEF-TV]]\n| former_callsigns         = KZJA ([[Construction permit#Broadcasting|CP]])\n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br>29 (UHF, 1994\u20132009)\n| former_affiliations      = '''Both secondary:'''<br>[[UPN]] (1995\u20131997)<br>[[The WB]] (1995\u20131998)\n| effective_radiated_power = 50 [[kilowatt|kW]]\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|513|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| facility_id              = 58618\n| coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|40|43|41.9|N|123|58|21.4|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = \n}}\n\n'''KBVU''', [[Virtual channel|virtual]] and [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[Digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 28, is a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]-[[Network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Eureka, California]], United States. Owned by [[Cunningham Broadcasting]], it is operated under a [[local marketing agreement]] (LMA) by the [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]], making it a [[sister station]] to [[Arcata, California|Arcata]]-licensed [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate [[KAEF-TV]] (channel 23). However, Sinclair effectively owns KBVU as the majority of Cunningham's stock is owned by the family of deceased group founder Julian Smith. It is also sister to two [[Low-power broadcasting#Television|low-power]] stations: dual [[The CW|CW]]/[[MyNetworkTV]] affiliate [[KECA-LD]] (channel 29), and [[Univision]] affiliate [[KEUV-LP]] ([[analog television|analog]] channel 31). The four stations share studios on Sixth Street in downtown Eureka; KBVU's transmitter is located along Barry Road southeast of Eureka.\n\nAlthough it identifies as a station in its own right, KBVU is considered a [[Broadcast relay station#Semi-satellites|semi-satellite]] of [[KCVU]] (channel 20) in [[Paradise, California|Paradise]]/[[Chico, California|Chico]]/[[Redding, California|Redding]]. As such, it clears all network programming as provided through its parent station but airs a separate offering of [[Broadcast syndication|syndicated]] programming; there are also separate local newscasts, commercial inserts and legal [[station identification]]s. [[Master control]] and some internal operations are based at the shared studios of KCVU and LMA partner [[KRCR-TV]] on Auditorium Drive in Redding.\n\n==History==\nThe station signed on the air as a Fox affiliate on July 20, 1994, replacing two satellite stations of [[KRCR-TV]] which broadcast both ABC and Fox programming. Prior to the launch of the station, the network's programming was only available via [[KAEF]] or [[KQSL|KFWU]] (which both carried the network as a secondary affiliation), while out-of-market affiliates [[KTVU]] and [[KTXL-TV]] were imported by some cable providers. \n\nOn April 21, 2017, [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] purchased KBVU as part of a four-station deal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Houston|first1=Will|title=Media giant Sinclair Broadcast Group to buy four Eureka stations|url=http://www.times-standard.com/article/NJ/20170421/NEWS/170429975|accessdate=10 July 2017|date=4 April 2017}}</ref> The sale was completed on September 1.<ref>[http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/prefill_and_display.pl?Application_id=1765804&Service=DT&Form_id=905&Facility_id=58618 Consummation Notice], ''CDBS Public Access'', [[Federal Communications Commission]], Retrieved 6 September 2017.</ref>\n\n==Digital television==\n\n===Digital channels===\nThe station's digital signal is [[multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>[http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=KBVU#station RabbitEars TV Query for KBVU]</ref>\n|-\n| 28.1 || [[720p]] || [[16:9]] || KBVU-DT || Main KBVU programming / [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n|-\n| 28.2 || [[480i]] || [[4:3]] || Cozi TV || [[Cozi TV]] \n|-\n|}\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nKBVU shut down its analog signal, over [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 29, on December 22, 2008, along with KCVU, due to lack of funding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and the Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=2012-03-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archivedate=2013-08-29 }}</ref> The station's digital signal broadcasts on its pre-transition UHF channel 28.\n\n==Newscasts==\nKBVU currently airs 2\u00bd hours of newscasts each week, all on weeknights at 10 p.m., as ''North Coast News on KBVU Fox 28 at 10''. The newscasts are produced by sister station KAEF.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Eureka TV}}\n{{Fox California}}\n{{SBGI}}\n\n[[Category:Fox network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Cozi TV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1994]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Eureka, California|BVU (TV)]]\n[[Category:Sinclair Broadcast Group]]\n", "name_user": "208.180.18.94", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KBVU_(TV)"}
{"title_page": "1992 United States presidential election in Hawaii", "text_new": "{{Main|1992 United States presidential election}}\n{{Infobox Election\n| election_name = 1992 [[United States presidential election]] in Hawaii\n| country = Hawaii\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1988 United States presidential election in Hawaii\n| previous_year = 1988\n| next_election = 1996 United States presidential election in Hawaii\n| next_year = 1996\n| election_date = November 3, 1992\n| image_size = x160px\n| image1 = Bill Clinton.jpg\n| nominee1 = '''[[Bill Clinton]]'''\n| party1 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Arkansas]]\n| running_mate1 = '''[[Al Gore]]'''\n| electoral_vote1 = '''4'''\n| popular_vote1 = '''179,310'''\n| percentage1 = '''48.09%'''\t\n| image2 = George H. W. Bush presidential portrait (cropped 2).jpg\n| nominee2 = [[George H. W. Bush]] \n| party2 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate2 = [[Dan Quayle]]\n| electoral_vote2 = 0\n| popular_vote2 = 136,822\n| percentage2 = 36.70%\t\n| image3 = RossPerotColor.jpg\n| nominee3 = [[Ross Perot]]\n| party3 = Independent (politician)\n| home_state3 = [[Texas]]\n| running_mate3 = [[James Stockdale]]\n| electoral_vote3 = 0\n| popular_vote3 = 53,003\t   \n| percentage3 = 14.22%\n| map_image = HI1992.jpg\n| map_size = 350px\n| map_caption = County Results\n'''Clinton'''\n{{legend|#b9d7ff|40\u201350%}}\n{{legend|#86b6f2|50\u201360%}}\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[George H. W. Bush]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsHI}}\n\nThe '''1992 United States presidential election in Hawaii''' took place on November 3, 1992, as part of the [[1992 United States presidential election]]. Voters chose four representatives, or electors to the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]], who voted for [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]].\n\n[[Hawaii]] was won by Governor [[Bill Clinton]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Arkansas]]) with 48.09% of the popular vote over incumbent President [[George H. W. Bush]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Texas]]) with 36.70%. Businessman [[Ross Perot]] ([[Independent politician|I]]-Texas) finished in third, with 14.22% of the popular vote, which was nonetheless Perot\u2019s poorest showing outside the District of Columbia and [[slave states and free states|antebellum slave states]].<ref name=results/> Clinton ultimately won the national vote, defeating incumbent President Bush. Clinton comfortably won Hawaii by a margin of 11.39%. It has only voted Republican twice since its statehood ([[1972 United States presidential election in Hawaii|1972]] for [[Richard Nixon]], and [[1984 United States presidential election in Hawaii|1984]] for [[Ronald Reagan]]). These Republican wins were landslides for Presidents Nixon and Reagan who both carried 49 out of 50 states. Hawaii has remained reliably Democratic since.<ref>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1992|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"6\" | 1992 United States presidential election in Hawaii<ref name=results>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results - Hawaii|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1992&off=0&elect=0&fips=15&f=0|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n|-bgcolor=\"#EEEEEE\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 17em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 5em