ted States presidential election]]. Voters chose four representatives, or electors to the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]], who voted for [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]].\n\n[[Hawaii]] was won by Governor [[Bill Clinton]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Arkansas]]) with 48.09% of the popular vote over incumbent President [[George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Texas]]) with 36.70%. Businessman [[Ross Perot]] ([[Independent politician|I]]-Texas) finished in third, with 14.22% of the popular vote, which was nonetheless Perot\u2019s poorest showing outside the District of Columbia and [[slave states and free states|antebellum slave states]].<ref name=results/> Clinton ultimately won the national vote, defeating incumbent President Bush. Clinton comfortably won Hawaii by a margin of 11.39%. It has only voted Republican twice since its statehood ([[1972 United States presidential election in Hawaii|1972]] for [[Richard Nixon]], and [[1984 United States presidential election in Hawaii|1984]] for [[Ronald Reagan]]). These Republican wins were landslides for Presidents Nixon and Reagan who both carried 49 out of 50 states. Hawaii has remained reliably Democratic since.<ref>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/national.php?year=1992|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"6\" | 1992 United States presidential election in Hawaii<ref name=results>{{cite web|title=1992 Presidential General Election Results - Hawaii|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1992&off=0&elect=0&fips=15&f=0|publisher=U.S. Elect